column2: Very heavy rains- almost 6" in past several days.
Rained again last evening- took gauge out today- will reinstall in May 1987.
Rained about 1" previous night and drizzled previous two days.
Too hot and dry this spring.
94 F today- 100 F projected for tomorrow.
Getting more clear after rain last weekend.
Level is from 7/10- after hard rain 7/8 in P.M.
Heavy rain over weekend- level 8.42 on 8/5.
Heavy traffic 6/24- lots of rain last week.
Quite windy- hard rain over weekend.
Overcast with SW winds at 5-6 mph.
Sunny- slight haze- hot- S wind at 8-10 mph- busy weekend.
Sunny- 51 F- wind at 12-15 mph- no notable algae bloom- rain gage over topped 2x last 2 weeks- lake was up to 8.36 on 9/17.  Had to return for heavier anchor - too windy.

Ice on 11/7 and off again on 11/15.  October too rainy and cold to do sampling.  The gauge was removed 11/13- water level then was 8.10.  Beautiful fall day- 54 degrees- calm- cloudy from 8am-1pm- had to put boat in to do tests.
Very wind- cloudy- and lots of rain yesterday.
Ample rain this summer- SW breeze @ 5 mph- rain is likely this P.M.
Nice warm august morning- south breeze 5-7 mph.

Very wet spring ith June rainfall totaling 12.25 inches. Partly cloudy skies. Temperature 87F with dew point 72F. Assisted by Robert Lawton. At the conclusion of the sample both of us jumped in the lake for a refrshing swim.

Winds 070 degrees @4 MPH. Ceiling 3600 feet broken. Temperature 22 Degree C. Dewpoint 4 degree . Barometer 30.09. Las rainfall on 8/4. Total rinfall to date August - .79 inch. Assisted by Captain Robert Lawton and his "gun boat".
Winds: 18 degrees @ 4 mph. ceiling: 6000broken. Temperature: 19 degree C.

column1: Pressure:30.25 Fall colors were outstanding. Specialthanks to Robert Lwton for his assistance. HACH LDO meter is so much bette than Van Dorn and Colormetric method.

column2: Skies: Clear. Temp.: 33 C. Winds: 290@7. Visability:  greater than  10 mi. Dewpoint: 16 C. Barometric Pressure: 29.87. Hot + Humid conditions past 2 days. Last rainfall 5 days prior. Special thanks to Capt. Bob and Miss Sandy for their much appreciated assitance and company on this mission.
Skies: mostly sunny Winds: 260@12 mph Temp: 22 CDewpoint:18 C Pressure: 29.85 Last rain 4 hours prior .25 inch. Last significant rain 4 days prior

Winds: Calm Visability:  greater than  10 miles. Skies: 100% clear.  Temperature: 18C Dewpoint: 16 C Barometer: 30.13 Rain in excess of 2.5 inches last Friday through Sunday. Would have very much liked to spend th rest of the day out on the lake. Only the October sample remains and another year of sampling will be complrtr. Special thanks to Capt. Robert Lawton for valuable assistance

Winds 010 deggrees @ 10 -13 mph. Skies: Scattered cloauds 3000 feet AGL Temperature: ^c Dewpoint: -2C. Barometer: 30.40. Temepature indicate North Basin has already turned over. Killing frosat occured fist week in October. Yet another year of lake monitoring has come to a close. Thanks to Bob Lawton for venturing out on the lake today on this cols and blustery October day

wunds 160 @ 6 MPH. Visability greater than 10 miles. Skies clear below 12-000 feet.Temperature 24 C Dewpoint 16 C presure 30.06. Early spring this year. Warm weather month of May but has cooled down for the month of June. Assisted by Capt'n Robert Lawton

Winds 160@6 MPH Skies clear. Temperature 22 C Dewpoint 17 C Barameter 30.01 On July 14th we received just over 5 inches of rain in a 9 hour period. The total accumulation of rain to date has exceeded the normal average for the entire month of July. Thanks to Bob Lawton for assiting in the taking of these measurements.
See previous comments from the same day South Basin
See comments for report Big Cedar Lake - South Basin dated 8 October 2010

Winds 220@12MPH Mixture of run and clouds all day with off and on again showers.Temp 22C Dew point 15C Pressure 29.52 inches It has been a unusually cold and wet spring. Paul Klien- Kristen kubisiak- and John Elke of the West Bend Daily News accompanied me for an articlethat appeared in the 23 June issue

Winds calm. Visability 10 miles. Skies clear.Temp 13 C. Dewpoint 11 C. Pressure 30.22. Rainfall so far this month .01 inch. Special thanks to Robert Lawton for his assistnace in gathering this data.

winds 030@7 Skies Clear visability  more than  10 miles Temperature 25C Dewpoint 11C Pressure 30.18. We have received zero rainfall since the second week in June . Last week over the 4th of July we had 3 days in excess of 100F. The remaoner of the week temperatures were in the 90"sF. Agin thanks to Bob Lawton for his assitance in obtaining this data.

Winds 060 degrees t 8 MPH- visability 10 miles- Skies Clear below 12-000 feet temp 16C- Dewpoint 7C- Pressure 30.23 Temps have been below normal past month (Lows 50 highs 75F) Not as many seagulls on the lake as previous years. Usually the lake is covered with them the month of August. Thanks to Bob Lawton for his assistance in gathering this data

Winds: Calm- Visability: 10 miles- Skies: Clear- Temperature 16c- Dewpoint 7c- Pressure: 30.12- Last rainfall 2 days prior  approximately .5 Inch No killing frost to date. No thermocline present in North Basin. Special thanks to Bob Lawton for his assistance this past summer. Last measurement to be take by this individual until 2014. Until then....Bye Bye    John.

winds 030 @ 6mph Visability 7 miles skies overcast with ceilings 700 feet temp 18c  dewpoint 15c  pressure 30.03 Daily rain for the past week and a half with 18 June  Nightly fog s total 3. inches. High humidity with cooler temps slight "ribbons" of alge visable. Thanks to Robert Lawto for his assistance on this sample.

Winds 080 @ 5 MPH Visability 10 miles. Skies clear below 12-000 feet. Temp. 22C. Dewpoint 17C Pressure  30.27. Last rain 38 hours ago (T-storm)  Unusually dry month so far. Thanks to Bob Lawton for his assistance gathering this data.
